    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a concise overview containing: 1) total row count; 2) minimum timestamp and maximum timestamp (as integers); 3) sorted unique cmdb_id values (limit to first 50 if more); 4) sorted unique KPI/trace/log name field values (kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv) (limit to first 50); 5) the top 5 rows (first 5) as examples with all columns. Keep outputs compact and labeled by filename."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output: metric.csv has 327,084 rows spanning timestamps roughly 1647873000–1647877000; trace.csv has 22,232 rows; log.csv has 1,570 rows; error_logs.csv is empty. We therefore have ample metric data to compute global thresholds. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must calculate global thresholds for each component-KPI using the full available series BEFORE filtering to the incident window (Mar 21, 2022 23:00–23:30). This step will let us detect anomalies in the incident window relative to each KPI's normal behavior. Next we should compute per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) statistics (global P95 and P5 at minimum) across the entire metric.csv and keep the result cached in the kernel for later filtering and anomaly detection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, aggregate the full available series (no time filtering) by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute these global statistics for each group: count, mean, min, max, 95th percentile (P95), and 5th percentile (P5). Store the result in a kernel variable (e.g., df_metric_kpi_stats). Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of the groups sorted by count descending, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, mean, min, max, p95, p5. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups detected. Keep output rows <=20."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor computed global statistics (count, mean, min, max, p95, p5) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group across the full metric.csv. There are 5,374 distinct groups, and the top groups by sample count include many adservice KPIs and a mesh.metrics group. With global thresholds available, the next step is to detect anomalies inside the incident window (Mar 21, 2022 23:00–23:30, UTC+8) by comparing metric values in that window against each group's global P95 and P5. We should detect both high anomalies (value >= P95) and low anomalies (value <= P5) because some failures manifest as drops (e.g., success rates). The goal of the next execution is to find which component-KPIs show consecutive anomalies in the incident window and to produce a compact ranked list of candidate faulty groups for deeper inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv to the incident time window March 21, 2022 23:00 to 23:30 using timezone UTC+8 (inclusive). Using the previously computed df_metric_kpi_stats (which has p95 and p5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name)), join those thresholds onto each metric row in the incident window. For each metric row, mark: high_anom if value >= p95, low_anom if value <= p5. Then aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) to compute: anomaly_count (number of rows with high_anom or low_anom), earliest_anom_timestamp (minimum timestamp among anomaly rows), anomaly_type (\"high\" if only high_anom rows, \"low\" if only low_anom rows, \"both\" if both kinds), and severity defined as maximum of these per-group measures: for high anomalies use max((value - p95)/p95) across high rows; for low anomalies use max((p5 - value)/ (p5 if p5!=0 else 1)) across low rows; if both present, take the larger severity. Store the incident-window filtered metrics and the anomaly-aggregates in kernel variables (e.g., df_incident_metric, df_metric_anoms). Return a compact table of the top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_timestamp, anomaly_type, severity. Also return the total number of groups that had anomaly_count > 0."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-21 23:00–23:30 UTC+8) by comparing each metric row against its group's global P95/P5. The anomaly table shows many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups with anomaly_count = 31 (i.e., anomalies present at every minute in the window) and severity = 0.0, and earliest_anom_timestamp = 1647874800. Many of these groups belong to adservice and shippingservice2-0, and some KPI names are mesh.* or container.node-6.*. Severity being 0.0 suggests measured values equal the group's p95/p5 thresholds (no relative exceedance beyond threshold), which can happen when metrics are tightly stable or thresholds match sampled values. We must now move from per-(cmdb,kpi) anomalies to per-component candidates (components limited to the provided possible root-cause list), ignoring mesh/middleware groups, to find which components show the most anomalous KPIs across the window. This will narrow candidate components for trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the incident-window anomaly table (df_metric_anoms), exclude KPI groups whose kpi_name contains the substring 'mesh.' (ignore mesh/middleware). Then aggregate by cmdb_id but only keep cmdb_id values that exist in the provided root-cause candidate list (node-1..node-6, all listed pod names and service names). For each cmdb_id compute: distinct_kpi_anom_count (number of distinct kpi_name with anomaly_count>0), total_anomaly_count (sum of anomaly_count across its KPIs), earliest_anom_timestamp (min among its KPIs), and max_severity (max severity among its KPIs). Return a compact table of the top 20 cmdb_id sorted by distinct_kpi_anom_count desc then total_anomaly_count desc, with columns: cmdb_id, distinct_kpi_anom_count, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anom_timestamp, max_severity. Also return the total number of distinct components (cmdb_id) that had distinct_kpi_anom_count > 0 after filtering."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level anomaly detection for the incident window (2022-03-21 23:00–23:30 UTC+8). After excluding mesh.* KPIs, aggregation by component shows many candidate components with persistent anomalies across the full window (anomaly_count = 31) and the earliest anomalous timestamp = 1647874800. Top candidates include adservice, several shippingservice instances, emailservice pods, frontend pods, recommendationservice pods, and others. Metric-level max_severity values suggest some components show strong deviations (e.g., non-zero max_severity), but many groups had severity 0.0 (values equal to P95/P5). According to the workflow, we must now use trace data to localize among multiple service/pod-level faulty candidates (select the most downstream faulty component in call chains). To proceed correctly we must compute global thresholds for trace KPIs across the full trace.csv series (before filtering to the incident window), then detect trace anomalies inside the incident window to identify which services/pods are actually faulty in traces and which are downstream.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, compute global statistics per (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full available trace.csv (no time filtering). For each group calculate: count, mean, min, max, p95, p5. Store the result in a kernel variable (e.g., df_trace_kpi_stats). Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of groups sorted by count descending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, mean, min, max, p95, p5. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) groups detected."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have global trace thresholds computed per (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full trace.csv (no time filtering). Metric analysis already found many components with persistent anomalies across the incident window and the earliest metric anomaly timestamp is 1647874800 (appears at the start of the 23:00 window). According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to localize the faulty component among multiple service/pod candidates by identifying which trace groups show anomalies in the same incident window and which faulty service/pod is the most downstream in call chains. We must detect trace anomalies in the incident window using the previously computed per-group global P95/P5 thresholds and produce a compact ranked list of anomalous trace groups for further localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter trace.csv to the incident time window March 21, 2022 23:00 to 23:30 inclusive using timezone UTC+8. Join the precomputed global trace thresholds (df_trace_kpi_stats) onto each trace row by (cmdb_id, trace_name). For each row mark: high_anom if value >= p95, low_anom if value <= p5. Aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) to compute: anomaly_count (rows with high_anom or low_anom), earliest_anom_timestamp (min timestamp among anomaly rows), anomaly_type ('high' if only high, 'low' if only low, 'both' if both), and severity (for high rows use max((value - p95)/p95) across high rows; for low rows use max((p5 - value)/p5) across low rows; if both exist take the max). Store results in kernel variables (e.g., df_trace_anoms, df_trace_anoms_top). Return a compact table (max 20 rows) of top trace groups sorted by anomaly_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_timestamp, anomaly_type, severity. Also return the total number of (cmdb_id, trace_name) groups that had anomaly_count > 0 in the incident window."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace anomaly detection for the incident window found many (cmdb_id, trace_name) groups with persistent anomalies starting at timestamp 1647874800 (the start of the window). Many trace groups report anomaly_type='both' and severity=0.0, but some duration-related traces (example: cartservice-1 trace.self.duration_mean/p95) show non-zero severity indicating measurable latency deviation. Metric-level aggregation earlier produced a ranked list of candidate components (adservice, shippingservice pods, emailservice pods, frontend pods, etc.) with many anomalous KPIs across the window.\n\nWhat we have done: computed global thresholds for metrics and traces, detected anomalies within the incident window, aggregated anomalies by component and by trace group. What can be derived: multiple services/pods are anomalous across the 23:00–23:30 window; some trace durations show significant severity (possible latency), while many error_rate/ss-like traces match thresholds exactly (severity 0.0). To localize the root cause among multiple faulty services/pods we must identify which faulty components are most downstream in call chains. A practical next step is to summarize, for the top metric-candidate components, their trace-anomaly patterns: how many anomalous outgoing calls (trace.to_), incoming calls (trace.from_), and self traces (trace.self), and the maximum trace severity. Components with many incoming/self anomalies but few/no outgoing anomalies are likely downstream and therefore stronger root-cause candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Take the top 20 components from the metric-level component aggregation (df_cmdb_agg sorted by distinct_kpi_anom_count desc). For each of these components, compute from the incident-window trace anomalies (df_trace_anoms) the following compact metrics: trace_to_anom_count = count of anomalous trace rows where trace_name contains 'trace.to_'; trace_from_anom_count = count where trace_name contains 'trace.from_'; trace_self_anom_count = count where trace_name contains 'trace.self'; trace_earliest_anom_timestamp = min earliest_anom_timestamp among its trace anomalies; max_trace_severity = maximum severity among its trace anomalies. Return a compact table (max 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, distinct_kpi_anom_count, total_anomaly_count, trace_to_anom_count, trace_from_anom_count, trace_self_anom_count, trace_earliest_anom_timestamp, max_trace_severity. Sort rows by distinct_kpi_anom_count desc then max_trace_severity desc. Also return the count of these top components that have trace_to_anom_count == 0 and (trace_from_anom_count > 0 or trace_self_anom_count > 0) (i.e., likely downstream candidates). Keep outputs <=20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds for metrics, traces, and logs (full-series P95/P5), filtered data to the incident window (2022-03-21 23:00–23:30 UTC+8), and detected anomalies. Metric analysis produced a set of top candidate components (adservice, frontend pods, recommendationservice pods, shippingservice pods, emailservice pods, cartservice-1, etc.) with persistent KPI anomalies across the whole window (many KPI groups had anomaly_count = 31). Trace analysis showed many anomalous traces beginning at timestamp 1647874800 (start of window) and identified components with substantial trace deviations (e.g., recommendationservice-1, frontend-2, cartservice-1). Log analysis restricted to the top-20 metric-anomalous components found 14 components with anomalous logs in the window (recommendationservice-2, adservice-0, adservice-1, shippingservice-2, paymentservice-2, currencyservice-2, shippingservice-1, frontend-2, recommendationservice-1, shippingservice-0, checkoutservice-0, emailservice-1, emailservice-2, emailservice-0). Recommendationservice-2 shows high log severity (0.974), and frontend-2 and several others also show significant log deviations.\n\nWhat we can derive so far: multiple services/pods show concurrent anomalies across metrics, traces, and logs starting at the same earliest timestamp (1647874800). To localize the root cause we must now examine the actual log entries and log-name-level aggregates for those anomalous components inside the incident window to identify concrete failure signals (e.g., error_count spikes, OOM, process terminations, disk/full messages, network errors). Since error_logs.csv is empty, the structured log.csv rows (log_name and value) are our primary log-source. We need compact, focused inspection of those anomalous components' logs (counts by log_name, earliest anomalous timestamp per log_name, and a few sample rows) to infer the underlying reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter log.csv to the incident time window March 21, 2022 23:00–23:30 inclusive (UTC+8). Restrict rows to the following components only: ['recommendationservice-2','adservice-0','adservice-1','shippingservice-2','paymentservice-2','currencyservice-2','shippingservice-1','frontend-2','recommendationservice-1','shippingservice-0','checkoutservice-0','emailservice-1','emailservice-2','emailservice-0']. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: row_count (rows in window), mean(value), max(value), earliest_timestamp (min timestamp). Also return up to 3 example rows per cmdb_id (columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value), but limit total example rows returned to 20. Return two outputs: 1) a compact aggregate table (<=20 rows) sorted by row_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, row_count, mean, max, earliest_timestamp; 2) the example rows (<=20). Also return the list of distinct log_name values found for these components in the window. Keep outputs bounded and store full intermediate tables in kernel variables for further steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the full workflow so far: computed global thresholds (P95/P5) for metrics, traces, and logs using the full-series data; filtered each source to the incident window (2022-03-21 23:00–23:30 UTC+8); detected anomalies per (cmdb_id,KPI) and per (cmdb_id,trace_name); aggregated anomalies to component level; and performed a focused log inspection for the top metric-anomalous components. Key observations: many components (adservice, frontend pods, recommendationservice pods, shippingservice pods, emailservice pods, cartservice-1, etc.) show persistent metric anomalies across the whole window (31 samples). Trace anomalies start at the same earliest timestamp 1647874800 (start of window). Some components show strong trace severity (recommendationservice-1, frontend-2, cartservice-1), and some components show strong metric severity (emailservice-0, shippingservice-0). Log anomalies (log.row_count spikes) are present for a subset (recommendationservice-2, adservice-0/1, shippingservice-2, paymentservice-2, currencyservice-2, shippingservice-1, frontend-2, recommendationservice-1, shippingservice-0, checkoutservice-0, emailservice-1/2/0). Error logs file is empty.\n\nWhat this implies: multiple services/pods are abnormal at once, all starting at 1647874800. To localize the root cause and the underlying reason we must inspect resource-related metrics (CPU, memory, disk, I/O, network, process failures) for the top candidate components (those with both metric anomalies and trace/log signals), and compare their incident-window values against their global thresholds to identify which resource deviates most and earliest. This will let us determine the root-cause component, the exact occurrence time (first anomalous timestamp of that resource KPI), and the reason (e.g., CPU/memory/disk/network/process).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the following candidate components: ['recommendationservice-1','recommendationservice-2','frontend-2','shippingservice-0','shippingservice-1','shippingservice-2','adservice','adservice-0','adservice-1','emailservice-0','cartservice-1','checkoutservice-0','currencyservice-2','paymentservice-2'], retrieve resource-related metric KPIs from df_metric_kpi_stats whose kpi_name contains any of these substrings (case-insensitive): 'cpu','memory','container','disk','io','read','write','net','packet','retrans','loss','latency','fail','process','thread','gc','heap'. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) listing for each matched (cmdb_id,kpi_name): count, p95, p5 from global stats. Then, using metric.csv filtered to the incident window (2022-03-21 23:00–23:30 inclusive, UTC+8), compute for each of these (cmdb_id,kpi_name) the window mean(value), max(value), earliest_timestamp in window, and compute severity as: for values above p95 use (max - p95)/p95, for values below p5 use (p5 - min)/ (p5 if p5!=0 else 1). If both sides present take the larger absolute severity. Store results in kernel variable df_resource_candidate_metrics and return the compact table sorted by severity desc (limit 20 rows). Also return the subset of rows where severity > 0.5 (strong deviations). Keep outputs bounded to 20 rows."
}

